Backcountry brown trout and meat pies from Fairlie,
Eighteen feet leaders that turn over rarely,
Snarfing the dry fly and then the reel sings,
These are a few of my favorite things.
 
Crystal clear water with nary an angler,
Long tramps and foam ants and hot springs near Hamner,
Bellbirds that sing with the cool Kiwi breeze,
These are a few of my favorite things.
 
Meeting new mates on the rivers I’m walking,
Joining up forces and upstream we’re stalking,
Stopping to grind up some fresh coffee beans,
These are a few of my favorite things.
 
When the emails bite,
When the bills sting,
When I’m feeling sad,
I simply remember my favorite things,
And then I don’t feel so bad!
🇳🇿 
.
.
.

For many years I never used a net to land redfish. They’re pretty easily landed by hand, but until I had one of these @fishpondusa Nomad nets I never really considered how much better it was for the fish. You can typically land a fish earlier with a net, and it’s much more effective for keeping them in the water while you unhook them and get ready for a quick picture before sending them back on their way. I always keep one on the skiff now.
📷 work by @l.z.jarrett.

The ultimate Surf and Turf.

On my way back from Antarctica this year I stopped in New Zealand and spent a few days with my good friend Matt (@flyfishingnz). We had plans to set off into the backcountry and fish a river early in the day before hiking into the hills in the afternoon to see about hunting up a Himalayan Tahr or a Red Stag.
The fishing was out of this world, the river was in perfect order and the numerous fish were all haphazardly chasing big dry flies. After getting our fill of the incredible fishing we headed back to camp, switched to hunting gear, and headed into the hills to look for animals. After a grueling climb to the top it wasn't long before Matt had glassed up a couple of bull Tahr. They were across a valley and on a facing hillside, presenting us with a long stalk to get around them, downwind, and in range. After closing the distance and low crawling to 160 yds I was able to harvest my first animal in NZ with just enough light left in the day to take a few pics and get it ready for the trek back to camp. As we made our way back in the dark, using headlamps to get us down the mountain and across the numerous streams, I couldn't believe how incredible the day had turned out to be.

Needless to say I'm now completely obsessed with these beautiful, tough, delicious creatures and the places they live. None of this would have been possible without the willingness of my buddy Matt to take time out of his busy schedule to make this happen and I'm eternally grateful for it. Many, many thanks, mate!
.
.
.

What a blessing to have this amazing display of cosmic energy show up during my week in Alaska with @rainbowriverlodge!
It had been raining and overcast all week when @amy_s_martin said that she and some of the other staff were hatching a plan to hike up to see if the skies would clear in time for the previously forecast auroras to take place. Once it was dark we all hiked up and sat in amazement, the skies had cleared and we watched in real time as energized particles from the Sun were redirected towards the poles by Earth’s magnetic field, causing the lights that we were witnessing first hand.
It was a magnificent display of God’s power and design, one that I will never forget.

The last slide is my attempt to have @billie_jo_clark there with me, I know it’s one of her dreams to see these and I hated that she wasn’t there. Next year, babe!
.
.
.
#alaska #rainbowriverlodge #aurora #auroraborealis #northernlights #nightsky #notripodnoproblem

I've posted this before, but it is most fitting to do so again on this weekend, which honors both the Marine Corps Birthday and Veteran's Day. I met Harry a few years ago in New Zealand, and he passed away shortly after we met. Thank you, Veterans. I am honored to have served my country as well, but never in such a great capacity as the story you're about to hear...
.
When you say hello to Harry, make sure to present a firm handshake and look him directly in the eyes. You see, that's a distinct sign of respect among men like him (and should be for all men, if you ask me...) and we, all of us, certainly owe Harry more respect than I could ever adequately put into words.
You see, Harry enlisted in the Marine Corps in 1940, traveling from Kansas to San Diego by way of train to attend USMC boot camp and earn his Eagle, Globe, and Anchor insignia. Shortly thereafter he was stationed in Hawaii when Pearl Harbor was attacked, and his immediate orders were to establish beach defenses for the landing assault that never came.
From there he was part of the assault landing force at four of the major Islands in the Pacific campaign, paving the way for US aircraft to draw closer and closer to mainland Japan for a final blow that would end the greatest war of all time.
He went ashore in the first waves at Guadalcanal, then Tarawa, then Saipan, then Peleliu. As a fellow Marine I sat, transfixed, as he told story after story of those campaigns, of his Kiwi wife and two sons, of the Korean war in which he served, and of how he loves the Corps and would rejoin if they let him. We talked about bourbon, about how his health is declining and he's frustrated that he's lost a lot of weight recently and is always cold. We talked about Chesty Puller, and he showed me a picture of his wife and Chesty cutting the USMC Birthday cake with an officer's sword on 10 November, 1949. Hanging on the wall next to his bar is a samurai sword that he took from Guadalcanal. (CONTINUED IN COMMENTS)
